        <div id="boxmodex2" class="clearfix">
            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            Life in Hong Kong and Our Immigration to Hawaii
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            evelyn li
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            When I was growing up in Hong Kong, the thing I remember most was that we lived in the garage. There were a lot of things that happened in the garage. At that time we were very poor. We had no house to live in, but we lived in a city, and a city has buildings and garages. So we lived in a two-car garage. Those people were very nice to allow us to live in their garage. There were about eight of us: my grandparents, my parents, four of us kids, and sometimes my auntie and uncle dropped by to live there. My grandpa was an opium addict. He was about sixty years old. I still remember how he looked: he sat on a chair and he was so skinny. He had asthma because he had been smoking opium so much, and we had no opium for him to smoke because we were so poor. He subsequently died. 
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <!--iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/113120001" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe-->
                        <iframe width="100%" height="166" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/189859745&amp;color=b6b6b6&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false"></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “Living in the garage, we had no bathroom, so we had to walk one or two blocks to go to some other association’s place. We snuck in to use their bathroom and snuck out.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            Living in the garage, we had no bathroom, so we had to walk one or two blocks to go to some other association’s place. We snuck in to use their bathroom and snuck out. Every time we did that, the kids always made fun of us. We also had no water. We had to walk about two blocks, up where there was a little hill. A bunch of us kids would run over there and get the hill water, which was pretty clean. There was a well there, too, so we got some water from there and took it to our house. <br />

            <br />The most pleasant time I have in my memory of Hong Kong was, believe it or not, during the typhoon season. My parents always went out to work and there was nobody home, and so the only time they were home was during the typhoon season. During that time we closed all the doors, all the kids were home, and the parents were home. That was the only time I felt comforted and happy. That would only last for two or three days, because the season would end and we would go out and see all of the trees on the ground. We were running around because that was the only time you smelled fresh air.  <br />
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                Why did we immigrate to the United States? It was because my dad had no job. We moved from apartment to apartment because we got kicked out. My dad would borrow some money and pay the downpayment for the deposit to rent an apartment. One of them was three hundred square feet, the other was two hundred square feet, for six of us. After one or two months he wouldn’t pay rent, so we got kicked out after one year. My dad was kind of smart; he was able to know the law enough for us to have free rent. But it was a horrible time, because we lived in Hong Kong at the worst time of all time. <br />

                <br />It was the lowest pit of capitalism. We had a lot of foreign invaders. We didn’t have enough to eat. I still remember going to bed hungry. My parents, needless to say, had no jobs. My mom would be somebody’s personal secretary, helping people doing scut work here and there, and my dad would be a hustler, going around learning how to gamble and stuff like that to make a few dollars to raise us. Before that he was an artist. He drew beautiful pictures and portraits on theaters. He was amazingly talented. My dad had two months of art class and was able to draw portraits vividly. It looked like the person was alive, and that was why so many theaters wanted him. But that was only for a short time, and then when bad times came, nobody watched movies anymore and we were back to this state of economic depression. <br />

                <br />In 1967 and shortly after, Hong Kong was so bad, the mafia basically ran the country. It was called a triad. They ran the country, and when the kids graduated from elementary school they either became prostitutes or went to work in the factories. In 1969 there was the really bad street revolt. Riots were in the street and people threw bombs in the street. We left Hong Kong two years before that, in 1967. <br />

                <br />Needless to say, we needed to look for a place to have prosperity. My parents were told that America had jobs. My Auntie Violet was so nice and kind. She got married to someone in America and sponsored us to move to America. After we came to America, we were very fortunate and my parents launched into jobs and my dad worked as an assistant cook in a Chinese restaurant. This was a skill he had to learn. He had to learn everything because he didn’t speak English. He made about $400 a month, and that wasn’t enough to feed the family, so my mom had to work in the pineapple cannery twelve hours a day, six days a week. <br />

                <br />We were a bunch of latchkey kids. I was eleven years old, my sister was thirteen, and my two younger brothers were nine and four years old at that time. At the age of eleven, I was the person responsible to cook for the whole house, because nobody had time to cook. When my mom came back home she was super tired, so I cooked for six people in my family, plus my grandma, which makes seven people. Lunch, dinner, and breakfast. My sister was the custodian of the family. She would wash dishes and clean the house.<br />
                </span>
            </div>

        </div>
