            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            Working My Way Out
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            evelyn li
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            What prompted me to be a cardiologist? I think it was the act of God. When I was kid, I was more interested in being an actress, because I saw them have fame and have control. But as I grew older, God’s hand had a lot to do with it. He made that happen. I don’t see how I could have made it happen. When I was a kid, healthcare was a big issue in our family. My parents were always reminding us that if it weren’t because of our going to the hospital, they would be millionaires. I don’t know how they could say that, but it definitely was very costly. 
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <!--iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/113120001" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe-->
                        <iframe width="100%" height="166" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/189859557&amp;color=d3d2d2&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false"></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “I said a prayer for two hours in bed when I was twelve years old. I was crying for two hours, and then I felt an angel talking to me.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            My mom said my brother and I took turns having seizures in our house. I was maybe six or seven years old, and he was five or six years old. My mom had no car to go to the hospital so she would beg her neighbors to take us, and sometimes she would have to pay a taxi to take us to the hospital. That really drained our money when we were already in poverty. There were times when we were not that sick, and we would stand in long, long lines to go to the hospital and we would have to pay money. I stood in line for two hours to be seen for a common cold. <br />

            <br />If people are sick, they shouldn’t be tortured in such a fashion. That prompted me to have interest in healthcare. But for me, being in such an impoverished state, having nothing in Hong Kong, becoming a doctor was undreamed of. It’s like thinking about something that is impossible. I think it was totally an act of God. <br />
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                When I came to America I was eleven years old, but I didn’t know how to speak English. Going to school was a horrific experience. We lived in the ghetto in Hawaii, and every day we were facing bullying, fights, and quarreling among the students. My friends got chased out of the room with a broom. One of the classmates would pick up a broom and chase her out. <br />

                <br />It had a lot to do with the language barrier, acceptance, or maybe racism - multiple reasons. We lived under that kind of strain, and for me, not able to express myself, it was a difficult time. Out of loneliness I decided to study. I also distinctly remember that I said a prayer for two hours in bed when I was twelve years old. I was crying for two hours, and then I felt an angel talking to me at that time. He said, “If you want to get out of the ghetto, I need you to study. Study hard.” It mobilized me. It motivated me to study harder. As I grew older, ages fourteen and fifteen, I was able to get some A’s because people from Hong Kong are good in math, and we automatically got 100 percent. <br />

                <br />I was studying the dictionary with my friend, because nobody taught us English other than the teacher, and the teacher was very busy taking care of all these violent kids. So we were studying the dictionary, practically word by word, and that’s how we studied for the SAT. Gradually we were promoted to a better section in our class and got some A’s, so in high school when I graduated, I was awarded a trophy for outstanding achievement in science. That was amazing. Unfortunately my mom had to work twelve hours a day, so she couldn’t even come to my graduation. I graduated with honors in high school and with my first trophy, and my mom couldn’t come. It was sad. But I was fortunate and got into UC Berkeley. <br />

                <br />I still remember when I first flew to Berkeley, I had maybe $50 in my pocket. I didn’t have a scholarship at the time, so my friend lent me $1,000 and my mom gave me a blanket. That was all I got to carry me to UC Berkeley. The first day, the first thing I did was go to the financial aid office. I said to them, “Here I am. I have no money.” They looked at my report card and saw that I had all A’s, and then they extended me the Regents’ Scholarship so I was able to finish my Berkeley education. Then I went to UC Davis for medical school. <br />

                <br />But it’s all the act of God. I felt like God’s hand was really working on me. When I was a kid, I was really lazy and didn’t want to do anything, but God had a way to make me become what I am today. If I hadn’t gone through the immigration, if I hadn’t suffered through the discrimination when I was a teenager, I probably wouldn’t have treasured the ethics, wouldn’t have treasured education, wouldn’t have treasured the values of a community. <br />

                <br />To make a long story short, it was good for me to go through all of that trial, learning to face adversity and going through all this alone. I was brought closer to God. Multiple times I would pray to him and it was he who watched me all the time. Because of that, when I was seventeen, I was brought to the church and baptized in the Mormon Church. <br />
                </span>
