                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “If he hadn’t put me in an environment where I was so deprived of friendship when I first came to Hawaii, I probably wouldn’t have wanted to study.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            Once a big pot of hot water poured over my whole belly when I was eight years old, and bubbles came out of my skin. My dad had no money to take me to the doctor. He said he read in the newspaper somewhere that all you had to do was put honey on top. So he did. He put honey on top of my belly for one week and it healed miraculously. It healed! There were a lot of maggots that swarmed around my belly for several days because of the honey, but now it is healed and has no scars, so you have to give credit to my dad. Even though we were poor and had no doctors, he was able to help us survive all those stormy years.  <br />

            <br />The draining of finances due to poverty and healthcare issues, together with living in the ghetto in Hawaii, prompted me to study hard. By studying hard, getting A’s in school, and getting trophies when I graduated from high school with honors, I was able to go to UC Berkeley with a full Regents’ Scholarship, and I was able to go to UC Davis Medical School with a full scholarship. I would say they were all acts of God. <br />

            <br /> If he hadn’t put me in an environment where I was so deprived of friendship when I first came to Hawaii, I probably wouldn’t have wanted to study. If I had had tons of friends in Hong Kong, I wouldn’t have wanted to study. If he hadn’t made my life such an impoverished situation, I probably would have had no need to study. God has made me a better person, to have more ambition, to be motivated, to excel in the world, and to learn to care for other people who have less than I do. That was my motivation to be a doctor.<br />
